    <subsection xml:id="secondorder01-subsection-second-order-linear-de">
        <title>Solving Second-Order Linear Equations</title>

        <p>Suppose that we have a homogeneous second-order linear differential equation with constant coefficients,
            <men xml:id="secondorder01-equation-constant-coef">a x'' + b x' + cx = 0.</men>
        The goal of this section is to be able to solve all such equations. To build some intuition, we start by considering the homogeneous <em>first-order</em> linear differential equation 
            <men xml:id="secondorder01-fo-equation-constant-coef">ax' + bx = 0.</men>
        Our work in <xref ref="firstlook"/> suggests that this equation has a solution of the form <m>x = e^{\lambda t}</m> for some constant <m>\lambda</m>. We can identify <m>\lambda</m> by substuting our guess for the solution into <xref ref="secondorder01-fo-equation-constant-coef"/> and solving algebraically. Since <m>\frac{d}{dt}e^{\lambda t} = \lambda e^{\lambda t}</m>, this substitution yields the equation
            <me>a\lambda e^{\lambda t} + be^{\lambda t} = 0.</me>
        Since the term <m>e^{\lambda t}</m> is always non-zero, we can safely divide both sides of the equation above by <m>e^{\lambda t}</m> to reach
            <me>a\lambda + b = 0,</me>
        which has solution <m>\lambda = -\frac{b}{a}</m>. Thus <xref ref="secondorder01-fo-equation-constant-coef"/> has <m>x = e^{-\frac{b}{a}t}</m> as a solution.
        </p>

        <p>A similar strategy works for homogeneous second-order linear differential equations. We <q>guess</q> that <xref ref="secondorder01-equation-constant-coef"/> has a solution of the form <m>x=e^{\lambda t}</m> and substitute our guess into the left-hand side of the equation. In detail, 

            <md>
                <mrow>a\left(\frac{d^2}{dt^2} e^{\lambda t}\right) + b\left(\frac{d}{dt}e^{\lambda t}\right) + c e^{\lambda t} &amp; = a\lambda^{2} e^{\lambda t} + b \lambda e^{\lambda t} + c e^{\lambda t}</mrow>
                <mrow>&amp; = (a\lambda^{2} + b\lambda + c) e^{\lambda t}</mrow>
            </md>

        Dividing out the non-zero term <m>e^{\lambda t}</m> as before, we see that <m>\lambda</m> must satisfy
            <men xml:id="secondorder01-equation-characteristic-eq">a\lambda^{2} + b\lambda + c = 0.</men>
        We call <xref ref="secondorder01-equation-characteristic-eq"/> the <term>characteristic equation</term> for <m>ax'' + bx' + cx = 0</m>. Its roots are
            <me>\lambda = - \frac{-b \pm \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}.</me>
        If <m>b^2 - 4ac \gt 0</m>, we get distinct real roots
            <me>\lambda_1 = \frac{-b + \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \quad \text{and} \quad \lambda_2 = \frac{-b - \sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a},</me>
        which correspond to a pair of solutions
            <me> x_{1}(t) = e^{\lambda_{1} t} \quad \text{and} \quad x_{2}(t)=e^{\lambda_{2} t}. </me>
        to <xref ref="secondorder01-equation-constant-coef"/>. Each solution <m>x_{i}(t)</m> exhibits exponential growth or decay depending on the sign of <m>\lambda_{i}</m>.
        </p>

        <example xml:id="secondorder01-example-real-solutions">
            <p>The equation
                <men xml:id="secondorder01-equation-guess">x'' + 3 x' - 10 x = 0</men>
                has characteristic equation <m>\lambda^{2} + 3\lambda - 10 = 0</m>. Rather than using the quadratic formula, we can simply factor the left-hand side as <m>(\lambda + 5)(\lambda-2)</m> to deduce that the roots are <m>\lambda =-5</m> and <m>\lambda=2</m>. The roots correspond to a pair of solutions to <xref ref="secondorder01-equation-guess" />:
                <me>x_1(t) = e^{-5t} \mbox{ and } x_2(t) = e^{2t}.</me>
            </p>
        </example>

        <p>The characteristic equation <xref ref="secondorder01-equation-characteristic-eq"/> also has distinct roots when <m>b^{2} - 4ac \lt 0</m>, although now the roots are <em>complex</em> numbers. Even so, we can make sense of the corresponding solutions using tools from [complex differential equations section]. In this case, it is customary to write <m>\lambda = \alpha \pm i\beta</m>, where
            <me>\alpha = - \frac{b}{2a} \quad \text{and} \quad \beta = \frac{\sqrt{4ac - b^2}}{2a}.</me>
        We then have a pair of complex conjugate roots
            <me>\lambda_{1} = \alpha + \beta i \quad \text{and} \quad \lambda_{2} = \alpha - \beta i</me>
        corresponding, as in the real case, to a pair of solutions
            <me>x_{1}(t) = e^{(\alpha + \beta i)t} \quad \text{and} \quad x_{2}(t) = e^{(\alpha - \beta i)t}.</me>
        We can rewrite <m>x_{1}(t)</m> as follows:
            <md>
                <mrow>x_{1}(t) &amp; = e^{(\alpha + \beta i)t}</mrow>
                <mrow>&amp; = e^{\alpha t + \beta i t}</mrow>
                <mrow>&amp; = e^{\alpha t}e^{\beta i t}</mrow>
            </md>
        From [Euler's formula], <m>e^{i\beta t}=\cos(\beta t) + i\sin(\beta)</m>, and so 
            <me>x_{1}(t) = e^{\alpha t}(\cos(\beta t) + i\sin(\beta t)).</me>
        Using the facts that <m>\cos(-\beta t)=\cos(\beta t)</m> and <m>\sin(-\beta t) = -\sin(\beta t)</m>, a similar computation on <m>x_{2}(t)</m> results in the expression
            <me>x_{2}(t) = e^{\alpha t}(\cos(\beta t) - i\sin(\beta t)).</me>
        To get real solutions, we can take the real part of <m>x_{1}(t)</m> and (negative) the imaginary part of <m>x_{2}(t)</m>. Going forward, we will use the resulting real functions as the canonical solutions to <xref ref="secondorder01-equation-constant-coef"/> when <m>b^{2} - 4ac \lt 0</m>, re-defining <m>x_{1}(t)</m> and <m>x_{2}(t)</m> as
            <me>x_{1}(t) = e^{\alpha t}\cos(\beta t) \quad \text{and} \quad x_{2}(t) = e^{\alpha t}\sin(\beta t).</me>
        Note that complex roots of the characteristic equation induce <em>oscillatory</em> behavior in the solutions of the differential equation due to the presence of the <m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> terms.
        </p>

        <example>
            <p>Consider the equation
                <me>x'' + 4 x' + 5 x  = 0</me>
                The characteristic equation is <m>\lambda^{2} + 4\lambda + 5 = 0</m>. The quadratic formula gives roots
                <me>\lambda = \frac{-4 \pm \sqrt{-4}}{2} = -2 \pm i,</me>
            corresponding to <m>\lambda = \alpha \pm \beta i</m> with <m>\alpha=-2</m>, <m>\beta = 1.</m> We get real solutions
            <me>x_{1}(t) = e^{-2t}\cos(t) \quad \text{and} \quad x_{2}(t) = e^{-2t}\sin(t).</me>
            </p>
        </example>

        <p>There is one more case to consider: when <m>b^{2}-4ac=0</m>. In this case, the charactersitic equation has a <em>repeated real root</em> at <m>\lambda = -\frac{b}{2a}</m>, which appears to give only one solution <m>x_{1}(t) = e^{-\frac{b}{2a}t}.</m> However, as demonstrated in the next example, it is possible to generate a second solution using the <m>x_{1}(t)</m>.
        </p>

        <example xml:id="secondorder01-example-reduction-of-order">
            <p>Consider the equation

                <me>x'' + 2x' + x = 0.</me>
            The characteristic equation is 
                <me>\lambda^{2} + 2\lambda + 1 = (\lambda + 1)^{2} = 0.</me>
            Thus, there is a repeated real root <m>\lambda  = -1</m> and we have a solution <m>x_1(t) = e^{-t}</m>.
            </p>

            <p>We seek a second solution that is not a multiple of <m>x_1(t) = e^{-t}</m>. We will <q>guess</q> that a solution to <m>x'' + 2x' + x = 0</m> of the form <m>v(t) x_1(t)</m> exists for some unknown function <m>v(t)</m> and attempt to solve for <m>v(t)</m>. Indeed, if 
                <me>x(t) = v(t) x_1(t) = v(t) e^{-t},</me>
            then
                <me>x'(t) = v(t) x_1'(t) + v'(t) x_1(t) = -v(t) e^{-t} + v'(t) e^{-t}</me>
            and
                <md>
                    <mrow>x''(t) &amp; = v''(t) x_1(t) + 2v'(t) x_1'(t) + v(t) x_1''(t)</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp; = v''(t) e^{-t} - 2 v'(t) e^{-t} + v(t) e^{-t}.</mrow>
                </md>
            Consequently,
                <md>
                    <mrow>x'' + 2 x' + x &amp; = [v'' e^{-t} - 2 v' e^{-t} + v e^{-t}] + 2 [-v e^{-t} + v' e^{-t}]  + [v e^{-t}]</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp; = e^{-t} v''</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp; = 0,</mrow>
                </md>
            and <m>v'' = 0</m>. Therefore, <m>v = c_1 t + c_2</m>. Letting <m>c_1 = 1</m> and <m>c_2 = 0</m>, we can assume that <m>v(t) = t</m>, and a second solution to our equation is given by 
                <me>x(t) = t e^{-t}</me>. 
            Note that we could just as well have chosen, say, <m>c_{1} = 0</m> and <m>c_{2}=1</m>, or <m>c_{1} = 1</m> and <m>c_{2}=1</m>. The former, however, results in <m>x(t)=e^{-t}</m>, which is the solution we already knew. The latter choice gives <m>x(t) = te^{-t} + e^{-t}</m>. While this solution is distinct from the one we started with, it still contains information from the original solution in the second term. The assignment <m>c_{1}=1</m>, <m>c_{2}=0</m> is the simplest choice of constants which gives in another solution that is, in a sense, <em>independent</em> from the first. This is a concept we cover in more detail in [section].
        </p>
        </example>

        <p>The technique that we have used in <xref ref="secondorder01-example-reduction-of-order" /> is called <term>reduction of order</term>. <idx>reduction of order</idx> In general, given a second-order linear differential equation
            <me>a x'' + bx' + cx = 0</me>
        such that <m>b^2 - 4ac = 0</m>, we have a pair of solutions
            <me>x_{1}(t) = e^{\lambda t} \quad\text{and}\quad x_{2}(t)= t e^{\lambda t},</me>
        where <m>\lambda = -b/2a</m>.
        </p>

